The bolt gap was gauged with an all matching bolt carrier associated to the rifle. The Carrier consisted of standard 8mm rollers that had been pitted and a worn locking piece to the bolt carrier. It read a .015 when the gauge went in without resistance, at .016 it has some interference and will not go all the way. I also tested 4 other matching carries,a and the gap ranged from .013 to .017; each fit in the receiver and closed up properly. Though of the five three were at the previous .015-.016 gap. Surplus parts are the trunnion, cocking tube, bayonet adater, front sight assembly, magazine release, and flash suppressor. Parts that are needed to fire the weapon stock, bolt carrier, bolt head, firing pin with spring, locking piece, stock pin, cocking tube support, cocking lever  with spring, recoilssembly, trigger group, selector lever, and lower.
